{"title_page": "Chris Kerson", "text_new": "Chris Kerson is an American [[film]], [[Television show|television]], and [[Theatre|theater]] actor. He is best known for his roles as [[True Detective (season 2)|Nails]] in ''[[True Detective]]'' and [[Gotti (2018 film)|Wilfred \"Willie Boy\" Johnson]] in [[Gotti (2018 film)|Gotti]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2015/08/10/meet-chris-kerson-the-actor-who-played-nails-on-true-detective/|title=Meet Chris Kerson, the Actor Who Played \u2018Nails\u2019 on \u2018True Detective\u2019|last=Calia|first=Michael|date=2015-08-10|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/whiteplains/lifestyle/westchester-native-plays-pivotal-role-with-john-travolta-in-movie-gotti/739279/|title=Westchester Native Plays Pivotal Role With John Travolta In Movie 'Gotti'|date=2018-07-01|website=White Plains Daily Voice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-gotti-review-20180615-story.html|title=Review: Overly reverent bio-pic 'Gotti' strands a solid John Travolta performance in less-than-epic drama|date=2018-06-15|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== Early Life ==\nChris was born in New York City and spent his childhood living between [[Manhattan]] and [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]]. He attended the [[College of William & Mary|College of William and Mary]] where he earned a bachelor's degree in [[Psychology]]. During his studies, he happened into an acting class, to satisfy an arts elective. He discovered a passion for the medium that would become his career. Immediately following graduation, he began frequent rotations between New York City and Los Angeles for work and continued development of his craft. \n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Film ===\nChris's filmography began with a role in Paul Duran's freshman feature, ''Flesh Suitcase'', which premiered at [[WorldFest-Houston International Film Festival|WorldFest Houston]] in 1995. He played lead in ''The RIde'', by NYU filmmaker and Martin Scorsese Scholarship recipient, Thomas Kim'','' of which Scorsese named best short film of the year.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2010, Kerson found critical and audience acclaim as the lead in Sean Kirkpatrick's Big Break Movie Contest feature ''Cost of a soul.'' The gritty drama about a combat soldier who returns to violence in the streets of Philadelphia opened in 50 theaters nationwide and screened at numerous festivals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://movieweb.com/exclusive-chris-kerson-talks-cost-of-a-soul/|title=Chris Kerson Talks \u2018Cost of a Soul\u2019 [Exclusive]|date=2011-05-18|website=Movieweb|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/cost-of-a-soul-1798168331|title=Cost Of A Soul|website=Film|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shockya.com/news/2011/05/16/chris-kerson-and-will-blagrove-talk-about-their-roles-in-cost-of-a-soul/|title=Chris Kerson and Will Blagrove Talk About Their Roles in Cost of a Soul|last=Benardello|first=Karen|date=2011-05-17|website=Shockya.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Catsoulis|first=Jeannette|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/20/movies/cost-of-a-soul-review.html|title=A Solemn Homecoming|date=2011-05-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/cost-a-soul-film-review-186251|title=Cost of a Soul: Film Review|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> Chris played a supporting role in [[Broadway's Finest]], the Jury Award winner of the 2012 Toronto International Film Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dcourier.com/news/2012/jul/27/broadways-finest-local-man-has-ties-to-featured-m/|title='Broadway's Finest': Local man has ties to featured movie at Prescott Film Festival|website=The Daily Courier|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> He followed that performance as a co-star in ''Another Zero in the System'' before working alongside [[Lance Henriksen]] in the cult [[Science fiction|sci-fi]] ''Daylight's End''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timmccannfilm.com/another-zero-in-the-system|title=ANOTHER ZERO IN THE SYSTEM|website=TIM MCCANN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=unclecreepy|title=Exclusive First Look: Daylight's End - Dread Central|date=2016-08-19|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/183900/exclusive-first-look-daylights-end/|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shockya.com/news/2014/02/03/daylights-end-offers-insight-sneak-preview-promo-trailer/|title=Daylight's End Offers Insight in Sneak Preview Promo Trailer|last=Benardello|first=Karen|date=2014-02-03|website=Shockya.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> Kerson won two best actor awards for his co-starring role in the 2019 suspense short ''Rendezvous''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dreamachinefilms.com/festival-winners|title=Award Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=Dreamachine International Film Festival|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iifilmawards.com/Gold_Award.html|title=Gold Award|website=www.iifilmawards.com|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/rendezvous/|title=Rendezvous {{!}} Film Threat|date=2019-12-09|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocmoviereviews.com/short-films/rendezvous-review/|title=Rendezvous Short Film Review|date=2020-01-07|website=OC Movie Reviews|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> \n\n=== Television ===\nKerson's work in television got started with a supporting role as Buck in the ''[[Pacific Blue (TV series)|Takedown]]'' episode of [[Pacific Blue (TV series)|''Pacific Blue'']]'s first season. In 2010, he nabbed an uncredited role as the Cool Camera Guy in the [[30 Rock (season 5)|College]] episode ([[30 Rock (season 5)|season 5, episode 6]]) of ''[[30 Rock]]''  Next, Chris played Gunnar in the [[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation (season 15)|Merchants of Menace]] episode in the 15th season of the hit show ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1651119/|title=Chris Kerson|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> In 2015 Chris landed his breakout role, as the recurring character [[True Detective (season 2)|Nails]] in the [[HBO]] hit [[True Detective|''True Detective'']].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://highlighthollywood.com/2014/12/hbo-taps-afema-omilami-and-chris-kerson-in-spots-for-true-detective-highlight-hollywood-news/|title=HBO Taps Afema Omilami And Chris Kerson In Spots For 'True Detective', Highlight Hollywood News|date=2014-12-06|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/06/new-details-on-the-true-detective-2-premiere.html|title=Here\u2019s a Description of the True Detective 2 Premiere|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/wynn-everett-cast-tnt-pilot-lumen-true-detective-afemo-omilami-chris-kerson-1201311414/|title=Wynn Everett Joins TNT Pilot \u2018Lumen\u2019; \u2018True Detective\u2019 Adds 2|last=Team|first=The Deadline|last2=Team|first2=The Deadline|date=2014-12-06|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> Nails is named for the scars he wears as the survivor of a nail gun attack. \n\n=== Theater ===\nChris has worked off-Broadway in a variety of theater roles. Early billings include Franz Xaver Kroetz' play ''The Nest''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatermania.com/shows/new-york-city-theater/off-off-broadway/the-nest_113322|title=The Nest (Closed July 23, 2005) {{!}} Off-Off-Broadway {{!}} reviews, cast and info {{!}} TheaterMania|website=www.theatermania.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=John Willis|first=Ben Hodges|title=Theater World 2005-2006: The Most Complete Record of the American Theater|publisher=Applause Theatre & Cinema Books|year=Jul 1, 2008|isbn=1557837082|location=https://books.google.com/books|pages=212}}</ref> and Stephan Morrow's ''Hurry'', which saw a sold out show at the Blue Heron Art Center. He played Carl the Usher in the New York premiere of [[Tennessee Williams]]' rediscovered play ''These Are the Stairs You Got to Watch''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/news/tennessee-to-the-rescue-of-13th-street-rep/|title=Tennessee to the rescue of 13th Street Rep|last=amNY|date=2007-03-20|website=amNewYork|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> Kerson also starred in Mario Fratti's ''Missionaries'' opposite theater icon [[Rose Gregorio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariofratti.com/trio-review-villager-staff/|title=Trio Review \u2013 Villager Staff {{!}} Mario Fratti, Playwright|website=www.mariofratti.com|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "text_old": "Chris Kerson is an American [[film]], [[Television show|television]], and [[Theatre|theater]] actor. He is best known for his roles as [[True Detective (season 2)|Nails]] in ''[[True Detective]]'' and [[Gotti (2018 film)|Wilfred \"Willie Boy\" Johnson]] in [[Gotti (2018 film)|Gotti]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2015/08/10/meet-chris-kerson-the-actor-who-played-nails-on-true-detective/|title=Meet Chris Kerson, the Actor Who Played \u2018Nails\u2019 on \u2018True Detective\u2019|last=Calia|first=Michael|date=2015-08-10|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/whiteplains/lifestyle/westchester-native-plays-pivotal-role-with-john-travolta-in-movie-gotti/739279/|t