, 2020|website=Nintendo}}</ref>\n|Octa-core (4\u00d7ARM Cortex-A57 & 4\u00d7ARM Cortex-A53) @ 1.020 GHz\n|}\n\n* The Nintendo Switch was released during this period, but has been referred to as a hybrid video game console, combining features of home and handheld systems. This is why the Switch appears in both the list of home video game consoles and the [[list of handheld game consoles]].\n\n== Upcoming consoles (The 9th Generation) ==\n\nThe following are announced home consoles for release in the near future:<ref>https://www.cnet.com/features/xbox-ps5-and-the-climate-crisis-next-gen-video-games-could-be-worse-for-the-planet/</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" id=\"9gencon\"\n|+\n!Name || Release date || Manufacturer || Units sold\n!CPU\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |[[PlayStation 5]]\n|Q4 2020\n|[[Sony]] {{flagicon|JPN}}\n|0\n|AMD Zen 2-based CPU with 8 cores at 3.5GHz (variable frequency)<ref>https://www.techradar.com/news/ps5#section-ps5-specs</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |[[Xbox Series X]]\n|Q4 2020\n|[[Microsoft]] {{flagicon|USA}}\n|0\n|8x Zen 2 Cores at 3.8GHz (3.6GHz with SMT) 7nm<ref>https://www.techradar.com/news/xbox-series-x#section-xbox-series-x-specs</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of best-selling game consoles]]\n* [[List of video game console emulators]]\n* [[List of video game consoles]]\n** [[List of dedicated consoles]]\n** [[List of handheld game consoles]]\n** [[List of microconsoles]]\n** [[List of retro style video game consoles]]\n** [[List of video games]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Notelist}}\n\n{{Home video game consoles}}\n{{video game consoles}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of video game consoles|*]]\n[[Category:Home video game consoles]]\n[[Category:Technology-related lists|Home video game consoles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{VG history|expandmenu=2}}\n\nThis is a '''list of home video game consoles''' in chronological order, which includes all known [[home video game console]]s after the first generation, from the first console, [[Magnavox Odyssey]], to the first ever [[ROM cartridge]]-based console [[Fairchild Channel F]], ranging from the major video game companies such as [[Magnavox]], [[Atari]], [[Fairchild Camera and Instrument|Fairchild]], [[Intellivision|Intellivision Entertainment]], [[Coleco]], [[Nintendo]], [[Sega]], [[NEC]], [[The 3DO Company|3DO]], [[SNK]], [[Sony]], and [[Microsoft]] to modern market consoles.\n\nThis list is divided into eras which are named based on the dominant console type of the era, though not all consoles of those eras are of the same type. Some eras are referred to based on how many bits a major console could process. The \"128-bit era\" ([[Sixth generation of video game consoles|sixth generation]]) was the final era in which this practice was widespread.\n\nThis list does not include other types of [[video game console]]s such as [[handheld game console]]s, which are usually of lower computational power than [[home console]]s due to their smaller size, [[microconsoles]], which are usually low-cost Android-based devices that rely on downloading, or [[dedicated console]]s past the first generation, which have games built in and do not use any form of physical media. Consoles have been redesigned from time to time to improve their market appeal. Redesigned models are not listed on their own.\n\n== Map key ==\nThere are a total of '''{{#expr:{{table row counter|id=2gencon|ignore=2}}+{{table row counter|id=3gencon|ignore=3}}+{{table row counter|id=4gencon|ignore=5}}+{{table row counter|id=5gencon|ignore=1}}+{{table row counter|id=6gencon|ignore=3}}+{{table row counter|id=7gencon|ignore=2}}+{{table row counter|id=8gencon|ignore=1}}}}''' video game platforms released since the second generation, and '''10''' canceled platforms.\n\nThis list only counts the first iteration of each console's hardware, because several systems have had slim, enhanced or other hardware revisions, but they aren't individually listed here. The list also includes unreleased systems. If a series of home video game consoles begins in a generation and lasts to another generation, it is listed in the generation the series began. This list does not claim to be complete.\n\n:{{legend|{{{1|#b6fcb6}}}|size=50%| ''Background shading indicates the [[List of best-selling game consoles|best-selling console]] of each respective generation.'' }}\n:{{legend|{{{1|#FFE8E8}}}|size=50%| ''Background shading indicates canceled systems that either stopped being developed at any stage or were canceled.'' }}\n:{{Legend|| outline = #FFFFFF|size=50%|{{Hash-tag}} ''Hash-tags indicate console series/platforms that have different hardware revisions.''}}\n\n== First generation (1972\u20131984) ==\n{{Main article|List of first generation home video game consoles}}{{See also|First generation of video game consoles}}\n\nThere were '''{{table row counter|id=genonecon|page=List of first generation home video game consoles|ignore=1}}''' home video game consoles known to have been released in the first generation of video game consoles. They can be found in the list of first generation home video game consoles.\n\n== Second generation (1976\u20131992) ==<!-- This is based on when the generation's last major unit was discontinued, not the release of the first unit in the next generation. 1992 is not a typo. -->\n{{See also|Second generation of video game consoles}}\nThere were a total of '''{{table row counter|id=2gencon|ignore=2}}''' home video game consoles released in the second generation, and '''1''' cancelled platform;\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Fairchild-Channel-F.jpg|[[Fairchild Channel F]] (November 1976)\nFile:RCA-Studio-II-FL.jpg|[[RCA Studio II]] (January 1977)\nFile:Bally-Arcade-Console.jpg|[[Bally Astrocade]] (1977)\nFile:Atari-2600-Wood-4Sw-Set.jpg|[[Atari 2600]] (1977)\nFile:APF-MP1000-FL.jpg|[[APF-MP1000]] (1978)\nFile:VC-4000-Console-Set.jpg|[[Interton VC 4000]] (1978)\nFile:Ac